snippet.textDisplay:
I too think that doubles serve no real purpose, with the pseudo-purposes being to show off ur balls and to save dirt and work.

Tables have less potential to harm u if u screw up and are much more solid than the shallow tips of a double's lip and landing. I wouldn't mind the extra work, if there is any extra work compared to doubles. I would argue that building 2 separate parts of the same jump is just as much, if not more work than building the same jump in 1 solid piece.

snippet.textDisplay: the rain is THE best time to dig dirt jumps! instead of just using water to get the dirt to harden on top once your done packing & shaping the jump, the rain helps water each layer of dirt you throw on the jump while your building it, leaving you with harder, stronger dirt, sooner. this also helps in the summer when things start to dry out because there is moisture all throughout the feature rather than just what's on top.

snippet.textDisplay: Sprinkle mortar mix (generic type n @ $2.50/bag) into your soil as you build...  It will dry the soil up significantly and firm it.  It's still going to act as soil and won't clump like you would think.  A few bags would do that entire lead-in berm.
